      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Substantive due process is a constitutional doctrine that protects fundamental rights and liberties by setting a standard for what the government can and cannot do without just compensation. This concept has been instrumental in expanding civil rights and personal liberties, particularly in cases like Griswold v. Connecticut (1965), which protected marital privacy, and Roe v. Wade (1973), which guaranteed women's reproductive rights. By limiting government overreach, substantive due process has allowed the courts to strike down laws that infringe upon fundamental freedoms.",
