      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "While it's true that judges may interpret and expand existing rights under substantive due process, the Constitution itself has always recognized that its text can be ambiguous and open to interpretation. The Founding Fathers deliberately left certain areas of law open to judicial review, entrusting the courts to apply the Constitution's principles and values to contemporary society. By doing so, judges can help ensure that the Constitution's fundamental protections continue to evolve and adapt to the changing needs of society.",
      "source": "target",
